In principle, $t_{\rm E}$ cannot be known perfectly from {\emph{WFIRST}}~for two reasons. First, {\emph{WFIRST}}~observations are not perfect, so the associated $t_{\rm E}$ measurement has a statistical uncertainty $\sigma_{\rm W}(t_{\rm E})$. Second, even if $t_{\rm E}$ from {\emph{WFIRST}}~can be constrained extremely precisely, $t_{\rm E}$ of the same event as seen from Earth is still uncertain to a limited level $\Delta t_{\rm E}$, due to the relative velocity between {\emph{WFIRST}}~and Earth. However, as we show in Appendix~\ref{sec:app1}, $t_{\rm E}$ for ground-based observations can be treated as ``perfectly'' known as long as the uncertainty in $t_{\rm E}$ inferred from {\emph{WFIRST}}~is smaller, by a certain specified factor (Equation~(\ref{eqn:condition})), than the uncertainty in $t_{\rm E}$ from ground-based observations. We have further proved in Appendices~\ref{sec:app1} and \ref{sec:app2} that this condition is almost always satisfied for both the {\emph{WFIRST}}~statistical uncertainty $\sigma_{\rm W}(t_{\rm E})$ and the {\emph{WFIRST}}-Earth systematic offset $\Delta t_{\rm E}$.

Therefore, the assumption that $t_{\rm E}$ is perfectly known from {\emph{WFIRST}}~almost always holds, so that $\sigma_2(t_{\rm eff})$ is mostly what we can get for the uncertainty in $t_{\rm eff}$ from ground-based observations.

Equations~(\ref{eqn:sigt0}) and (\ref{eqn:sigteff}) have a number of important implications. First, the two terms entering ${{\mbox{\boldmath$\Lambda$}}}$ have exactly the same errors in the high magnification limit, namely $\sqrt{8 t_{\rm eff}/\pi\Gamma}\sigma_0/F_{\rm peak}$. Second, the errors scale strongly with magnification, $\propto u_0^{3/2}$ times the correction factor. This implies a strong magnification bias, so that the much more numerous faint potential sources can relatively easily enter the sample at high magnification. The magnification bias is stronger for $\sigma(t_{\rm eff})$ than for $\sigma(t_0)$, suggesting that $\pi_{{\rm E},\parallel}$ is always better determined than $\pi_{{\rm E},\perp}$. However, comparison of $g(u_0)$ and $h_2(u_0)$ shows that this superiority is relatively modest.

Third, $t_0$ is not correlated with other parameters, and in particular it is not correlated with $t_{\rm eff}$. This is simply due to the fact that $\partial F/\partial t_0$ is an odd function of $t$, while the other derivatives are even in $t$. This is true for both Equations~(\ref{eqn:partials_general}) and (\ref{eqn:dlimit}).

Fourth, $t_{\rm eff}$ is correlated with other parameters. As the first indication of why this is important, we note that even in the high-magnification limit, $t_{\rm eff}$ remains significantly correlated with $F_{\rm peak}$ (correlation coefficient $-\sqrt{2/3}$). Hence, for example, if there were independent information about the source flux, the error in $t_{\rm eff}$ could be reduced by a factor up to $\sqrt{3}$.

To make a quantitative estimate of the microlens parallax errors, we adopt parameters typical of KMTNet. We assume $\Gamma_\oplus=240\,{\rm day}^{-1}$, i.e., one observation per 2 minutes, for four hours per night (which is the time the Bulge is visible at the midpoint of the \emph{WFIRST} campaigns) at each of three observatories, and 33\% bad weather. We normalize the errors to 0.05 magnitudes at $I=18$.
\footnote{The Vega magnitude system is used in the present work.}
We then find

