We illustrate this sensitivity in Figure~\ref{fig:fullpar} by showing the number of events that satisfy $\pi_{\rm E}/\sigma(\pi_{{\rm E},\parallel})> 5$ (or $\pi_{\rm E}/\sigma(\pi_{{\rm E},\perp})> 5$) for typical Bulge lenses ($\tilde v = {\rm AU}\mu_{\rm rel}/\pi_{\rm rel}=1000\,{\rm km~s^{-1}}$) and typical disk lenses ($\tilde v = 280\,{\rm km~s^{-1}}$). Here we have assumed $A_I=1.5$ and then integrated over the \citet{Holtzman:1998} luminosity function. The Figure is normalized to the number of events with {\emph{WFIRST}}~baseline photometric precision better than 1\%. This number can in turn be estimated for any specific \emph{WFIRST} strategy that is either considered or adopted, and of course can be empirically determined from the experiment itself.

There are several important points regarding Figure~\ref{fig:fullpar}. First, by incorporating the $t_{\rm E}$ information from {\emph{WFIRST}}~observations, we are able to increase the number of 2-D parallax detections by a factor $\sim$1.2. Second, the full parallax (${\mbox{\boldmath${\pi}$}}_{\rm E}$) curves with and without incorporating $t_{\rm E}$ information from {\emph{WFIRST}}~lie only about a factor of 1.2 and 1.5 below the $\pi_{{\rm E},\parallel}$ curves, respectively, despite the more serious deteriorations of $h_i(u_0)$ relative to $g(u_0)$ shown in Figure~\ref{fig:func_u0}.
